06–Deceased","5 April 1357":"5 April 1357","1330":"1330","1285":"1285","1350":"1350","1380":"1380","before 1328":"before 1328","1357":"1357","1345":"1345","1420":"1420","1353":"1353","about 1345":"about 1345","January 1345":"January 1345","1328":"1328","1306":"1306","Glenorchy, Argyll, Scotland":"Glenorchy, Argyll, Scotland","Lochgoilhead, Argyll, Scotland":"Lochgoilhead, Argyll, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland","Argyll, Scotland":"Argyll, Scotland","Lochawe, Argyll, Scotland":"Lochawe, Argyll, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Campbell","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: nickname from Gaelic <i>cam</i> ‘crooked, bent’ + <i>beul</i> ‘mouth’. As a result of folk etymology, the surname was often represented in Latin documents as <i>de bello campo</i> ‘of the fair field’, which led to the name sometimes being ‘translated’ into Anglo-Norman French as   Beauchamp  .","Irish (North Armagh): adopted for Gaelic <b>Mac Cathmhaoil</b> ‘son of Cathmhaol’ (literally ‘battle chief’): see   Caulfield   and   Cowell  .","English: variant of   Camel  , under the influence of the Scottish name (see 1 above)."],"variants":[{"name":"Camble","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Campbell  ."]},{"name":"Campbel","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Campbell  ."]},{"name":"Cambell","meanings":["(1997: 229;2007: 1415; 2010: NA)","Scottish: variant of   Campbell  ."]},{"name":"Campell","meanings":["(2007: 398; 2010: NA)","Scottish (Lanarkshire) and English: variant of   Campbell   (see also   Camel  )."]},{"name":"Beauchamp","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Antoine, Jacques, Yves, Andre, Armand, Emile, Fernand, Marcel, Marthe, Remi, Alcide, Camille.","English (of Norman origin) and French: habitational name from any of several places in France, for example in Manche and Somme, that are named with Old French <i>beu</i>, <i>bel</i> ‘fair, lovely’ + <i>champ(s)</i> ‘field, plain’ (from Latin <i>bello campo</i> ‘beautiful field’). In English the surname is generally pronounced   Beecham  . Compare   Bushaw  .","English: in some cases, an Anglo-Norman French adaptation of Scottish   Campbell  , by translation into French of the folk etymology <i>de campo bello</i> ‘from the fair field’."]},{"name":"Camel","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Napoleon, Patrice.","English (of Norman origin) and French: nickname from Norman French <i>came(i)l</i> ‘camel’ (from Latin <i>camelus</i>, classical Greek <i>kamēlos</i>), possibly denoting a clumsy person or someone with long legs. It may also be a topographic or habitational name referring to a house with a sign depicting a camel (although surnames derived from house and inn signs are rare in English); compare 5 below.","English: possibly a habitational name from Queen Camel and West Camel in Somerset, early recorded as <i>Camel(le)</i>, possibly a Celtic name from <i>canto-</i> ‘border, district’ and <i>mēl</i> ‘bare hill’."]}]},{"name":"Mariota","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Pet form of   María ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Mariota Campbell was born in 1328, in Glenorchy, Argyll, Scotland, her father, Iain Campbell Of Ardscotnish, was 43 and her mother, Mariata MacGregor, was 22. She married John Campbell about 1345, in Argyll, Scotland. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. She died on 5 April 1357, in Lochawe, Argyll, Scotland, at the age of 29, and was buried in Lochawe, Argyll, Scotland."},"et":{"1328–5 April 1357":"1328–5. aprill 1357","1328–1357":"1328–1357","1330–1380":"1330–1380","1345–1420":"1345–1420","1350–Male":"1350–Surnud","1285–1353":"1285–1353","1306–Female":"1306–Surnud","5 April 1357":"5. aprill 1357","1330":"1330","1285":"1285","1350":"1350","1380":"1380","before 1328":"enne 1328","1357":"1357","1345":"1345","1420":"1420","1353":"1353","about 1345":"umbes 134